---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const toml = `# EasyTier config the client joins with
dhcp = true
[network_identity]
network_name = "my-smp"
network_secret = "shared-secret"
[[peer]]
uri = "tcp://relay.example.com:11010"

# where the Minecraft server lives on the mesh
# (etmc extension; stripped before EasyTier sees it)
[etmc]
server = "10.144.144.1:25565"
label  = "My SMP"`;
---

<DocsLayout title="Connect via config URL" description="Join an EasyTier-networked server from a hosted config file.">
  <p>
    Server admins can publish a single config file over HTTP(S) so players join with just a link —
    no join code. In the menu choose <strong>Connect via config URL</strong>, or run
    <code>/etmc connect &lt;url&gt;</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>The config file</h2>
  <p>It's a normal EasyTier TOML (network, relay, addressing) plus an optional etmc block naming the
    in-mesh Minecraft server:</p>
  <pre><code>{toml}</code></pre>

  <p>etmc fetches it, forces <code>no_tun</code>, joins the mesh, and tunnels to <code>server</code>.
    If the file omits <code>[etmc] server</code>, fill the Server field (or pass <code>ip:port</code> to the
    command). An <code>ETMC1:…</code> join code at the URL works too.</p>

  <div class="note">
    The target server does <strong>not</strong> need to run etmc — it only needs to be reachable on the
    EasyTier network (for example a server box already running EasyTier).
  </div>

  <h2>Generate one</h2>
  <p>Use the <a href="/generator">config generator</a> to build and download the file in your browser, then host it anywhere (a gist raw link, your site, R2…).</p>
</DocsLayout>
